menu "ZHAC RainMaker bridge"

config ZHAC_RAINMAKER_ENABLE
    bool "Enable ESP RainMaker uplink bridge"
    default n
    help
        Compile the rainmaker_gw component's real bridge logic and pull the
        espressif/esp_rainmaker managed dependency (rules-gated in
        main/idf_component.yml, so a flag-off build resolves zero new
        components / managed_components entries). OFF (default):
        rainmaker_gw's public API compiles to inert stubs that always
        report RMK_ST_DISABLED — no esp_rainmaker code is linked.

        Also requires the runtime uplink selector (zap_store's
        zhac_uplink_get()) to be set to RainMaker before the bridge
        actually does anything; this flag alone only controls what gets
        COMPILED.

config ZHAC_RAINMAKER_NODE_NAME
    string "RainMaker node name"
    depends on ZHAC_RAINMAKER_ENABLE
    default "ZHAC"
    help
        Node name reported to the RainMaker cloud during claim/provisioning
        (Task 13+).

config ZHAC_RMK_MIN_REPORT_INTERVAL_S
    int "Minimum seconds between RainMaker reports for a continuous param"
    depends on ZHAC_RAINMAKER_ENABLE
    default 30
    range 5 600
    help
        Rate-limit for the bridge OUT direction on CONTINUOUS (non-boolean)
        params — temperature, humidity, brightness, colour temperature. A
        Zigbee sensor can report several times per second, but RainMaker's
        MQTT budget only refills one publish token every 5 seconds (and the
        public cloud deactivates nodes exceeding ~25,000 messages/day). Left
        unthrottled, a chatty sensor drains the budget so command reports
        (socket toggles etc.) get silently dropped — the exact "changes do
        not apply on the RainMaker side" failure this guards against.

        Only continuous params are throttled: boolean events (on/off,
        occupancy, contact) and user commands (which set `force`) always
        report immediately. Raise this if you bridge many continuous sensors;
        lower it (min 5 s) if you need fresher telemetry and publish little
        else. This does not affect the LAN Web UI, which is never throttled.

endmenu
